replyContent: Nonsense. The file access permission is to allow the app to export a config file for the custom conversions and constants, and only gets the permission if you agree to it when you use this feature. More importantly, the app can't send any information to anyone as it has no internet access. You can check this for yourself in the permissions too.

content: I've been using this for years and love it to pieces. However, lately there's a noticeable delay between pressing a key and the app reacting. The result is that I can't use it quickly any more as I have to pause after each key press. Maybe it's a result of the Android 9 update? Update: you are 100% correct! Thank you. Accessibility was the culprit (ironically). I have disabled the triple tap option and all is well in the world again. At least it would be if only Trump was removed from office.
replyContent: Hi. The delay is probably because you have one of the magnification options enabled in your phone's accessibility settings. This introduces a delay before taps are sent to the app, nothing can be done about this from within the app, but if you don't need the magnification feature then disabling it should fix the delay.

Too basic for an app that should have at least matched what a real scientific calculator can do. First, the most glaring omission is the ability see the whole equation while you type. Without it, you won't know if you've typed a long equation correctly or not. It's like this app throws us back to the early 80's. Too primitive You're supposed to simulate a modern scientific calculator you can buy today.  Second, you cannot edit the equation you typed in. In instances where you find the result to be erroneous, you cannot go back to review and edit the equation. Third, waste of screen real estate. Why make the numeric keys abnormally big? It's very unnatural switching from a real calculator to this app. You should have increased the simulated LCD instead, to allow it to show two or three lines of characters. That way, you can view both the input equation and calculated result simultaneously, which will be a big help in hunting down typo errors. You can also add another line of function buttons at top row. Free up the most commonly used functions to that additional row, instead of cramming all of it into "shift" sub-buttons. PowerCalc did it perfectly. Copying exactly the look and feel of an advanced Casio scientific calculator. (Don't know why that app disappeared from Google Play. Did you have anything to do with it?)

By holding get down the "recent apps" (bottom left corner) while the app is open, brings up a "settings" menu for that specific app. This is a great app, & a great developer!

RealCalc  just offers clear and easy-to-operate buttons and operational modes, with some enhancements appropriate for the more flexible environment of Android touchscreen. The only wish is that it would have a variable-size capability for tablets - filling the screen area is perfect for phones but a little silly on a 10" or 12" tablet. I would love to contribute to further development but no contact info is given; seems the developer has moved on to other projects.

As a land surveyor, I work with trigonometry all day, and while I have dedicated machines costing many thousands of dollars, none of that software is written as well as this little $4 app.   I am very picky about what I use for a calculator; in fact I like the Casio fx-5000 (now $80 on eBay) the best of all I've used, and that includes custom programmed HP 48GXs to the tune of $4,000 cards.   This app truly has it all. It works effortlessly with degrees, minutes & seconds, all the trig functions, inverses, logs, easy conversions (! - OMG), and tons more. Fractions are handled WAY better than on my Construction Master calculator ($80). It goes back and forth from algebraic to RPN, depending on my mood, keeps a history of answers you can put on the stack, turns sideways easily, and all for $4.   In short, I am hard pressed to even suggest an improvement to RealCalc. I guess I'd have to say that instead of converting anything to furlongs, it should convert them to rods. It does convert to chains, by the way. Ha!   This guy should be as rich as Bill Gates, and better deserve it.
